definition.value: A 3-hydroxy steroid that is obtained by formal dehydrogenation across positions 6 and 7 of 17beta-estradiol.
A 3-hydroxy steroid that is obtained by formal dehydrogenation across positions 7 and 8 of 17beta-estradiol.
A steroid acid that consists of 17beta-estradiol bearing an N-(carboxymethylamino)carbonylmethoxy at the 6beta-position
A polysaccharide composed of a backbone of repeating alpha-L-rhamnosyl-(1->2)-alpha-L-rhamnosyl units, joined by (1->3)-linkages.
A sesquiterpene that consists of cyclohexane bearing methyl and vinyl substituents at position 1 as well as two isopropenyl substituents at positions 2 and 4.
The (-)-enantiomer of beta-elemene that has (1S,2S,4R)-configuration.

A sulfur-containing amino acid in which the gamma-carbon atoms of two molecules of L-aminobutyric acid are joined via a thioether linkage. It is a byproduct of cystathionine-gamma-lyase and a possible human hyperhomocysteinemia marker.
A glycosylgalactose consisting of D-galactose having an alpha-L-fucosyl residue attached at the 2-position.

An oligosaccharide phosphate that is beta-D-Man-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcA-(1->2)-alpha-D-Man-(1->3)-beta-D-Glc-(1->4)-alpha-D-Glc-1-diphospho-ditrans,polycis-undecaprenol in which the terminal mannosyl group has been converted to its 4,6-O-1-carboxyethylidene derivative.
alpha-D-GalpN-(1->3)-[alpha-L-Fucp-(1->2)]-D-Galp in which the configuration of the anomeric carbon of the galactose residue at the reducing end is beta.

An organophosphate oxoanion that is the tetra-anion of 4,6-Me(COOH)C-beta-D-Man-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcA-(1->2)-alpha-D-Man-(1->3)-beta-D-Glc-(1->4)-alpha-D-Glc-1-diphospho-ditrans,polycis-undecaprenol arising from deprotonation of both free diphosphate OH groups and both of the carboxy groups; major species at pH 7.3.
A cardiolipin derivative in which all four of the phosphatidyl acyl groups are specified as stearoyl (octadecanoyl).
A cardiolipin derivative in which all four of the phosphatidyl acyl groups are specified as myristoyl (tetradecanoyl).
A 2,2'-dilyso cardiolipin in which both of the phosphatidyl acyl groups are specified as linoleoyl.
An oligosaccharide comprised of xylose residues.

A myo-inositol cyclic phosphate that consists of 1D-myo-inositol 1,2-cyclic phosphate having an octasaccharide moiety made up from four alpha-galactosyl residues, three alpha-mannosyl residues and one alpha-glucosaminyl residue, which at the reducing end is attached at position 6 via a glycosidic linkage.
A nucleoside residue in which an adenosine residue has been modified by substitution at C-2 by a methylthio (methylsulfanyl) group and at the 6-amino nitrogen by a Delta(2)-isopentenyl group.
A triterpenoid saponin that is composed of soyasapogenol B having a beta-D-galactopyranosyl-(1->2)-beta-D-glucopyranosiduronic acid moiety attached at the 3-position via a glycosidic linkage.
Any compound that is able to prevent damage to the liver.
A glycotriaosylceramide having N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosaminyl-(1->3)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucose as the glycotriaosyl component.
A glycotetraosylceramide having beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosaminyl-(1->3)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucose as the tetrasaccharide component.
An EC 4.3.* (C-N lyase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of phenylalanine ammonia-lyase (EC 4.3.1.24).
An EC 1.2.3.* (oxidoreductase acting on donor aldehyde/oxo group with oxygen as acceptor) inhibitor which interferes with the action of aldehyde oxidase (EC 1.2.3.1).
An agonist that selectively binds to and activates an odorant receptor.

A 3beta-sterol that is 5alpha-androstane which contains a double bond between positions 7 and 8, in which the hydrogens at the 3beta, 5alpha and 6beta positions are substituted by hydroxy groups, and in which the hydrogen at the 17beta position is substituted by a (2S,3E,6xi)-6,7-dimethyloct-3-en-2-yl group. The polyhydroxylated C29 sterol was isolated from an endophytic fungus, Chaetomium globosum ZY-22; the stereochemistry at position 25 was not determined.
A nucleoside analogue in which adenosine has been modified by substitution at C-2 by a methylthio (methylsulfanyl) group and at the 6-amino nitrogen by a Delta(2)-isopentenyl group.
A thiopyranopyrimidine that is 1,5,7,8-tetrahydro-4H-thiino[4,3-d]pyrimidin-4-one which is substituted at position 2 by a p-(aminomethyl)phenyl group.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of 2-deoxy-D-ribose 5-monophosphate; major microspecies at pH 7.3.
A thiopyranopyrimidine in which a 7,8-dihydro-5H-thiopyrano[4,3-d]pyrimidine skeleton is substituted at C-4 by a hydroxy group and at C-2 by a para-(trifluoromethyl)phenyl group.
A nucleoside analogue in which adenosine has been modified by substitution at C-2 by a methylthio (methylsulfanyl) group and at the 6-amino nitrogen by a cis-4-hydroxy-Delta(2)-isopentenyl group.
A benzimidazole substituted with a carbamoyl group at C-4 and a (2R)-2-methylpyrrolidin-2-yl moiety at C-2.  It is a potent, orally bioavailable PARP inhibitor.
A nucleoside analogue in which adenosine has been modified by substitution at the 6-amino nitrogen by a Delta(2)-isopentenyl group.
A dicarboximide having an endo bridged phthalimide structure, substituted at nitrogen by a 4-(quinolin-8-ylcarbamoyl)benzoyl group.
A dicarboximide having an exo bridged phthalimide structure, substituted at nitrogen by a 4-(quinolin-8-ylcarbamoyl)benzoyl group. It is a weak axin stabilizer, an analogue of  IWR-1-endo.
A nucleoside residue in which an adenosine residue has been modified by substitution at the 6-amino nitrogen by a Delta(2)-isopentenyl group.
The nucleoside residue formed from adenosine with linkages at the 3' and 5' positions.
Any organic heterobicyclic compound containing ortho-fused thiopyran and pyrimidine rings.
Any compound that inhibits the action of tankyrase.
An organic diphosphate formed by condensation of diphosphoric acid with allyl alcohol.
An organic phosphate ester formed by condensation of diphosphoric acid with one or more alcohols.
The organophosphate oxoanion that is 2-(2-carboxy-4-methylthiazol-5-yl)ethyl phosphate protonated to pH 7.3
A primary alcohol in which the hydroxy function is bonded to a CH3CH=CHCH2- (crotyl) group.
An organic diphosphate formed by condensation of diphosphoric acid with crotyl alcohol.
An organic triphosphate formed by condensation between the gamma-phospho group of uridine 5'-triphosphate and allyl alcohol.
An organic phosphate ester formed by condensation of triphosphoric acid with one or more alcohols.
An organic triphosphate formed by condensation between the gamma-phospho group of uridine 5'-triphosphate and crotyl alcohol.
An organic triphosphate formed by condensation between the gamma-phospho group of uridine 5'-triphosphate and prenol (gamma,gamma-dimethylallyl alcohol).
An organic triphosphate formed by condensation between the gamma-phospho group of uridine 5'-triphosphate and isopentenyl alcohol.
A primary alcohol having the structure of isopentyl alcohol but with a double bond between C-3 and one of the C-4 atoms.
The organophosphate oxoanion that is the 2R,5Z isomer of 2-carboxylato-4-methyl-5-[(2-phosphonatooxy)ethylidene]-2,5-dihydrothiazole(3-); protonated to pH 7.3.
